HashMap in Java (Deep Dive)

HashMap stores data as key → value pairs and provides very fast operations using hashing.

How HashMap Works Internally
Step-by-step (put operation)
map.put("Apple", 10);

👉 What happens internally:

hashCode() is called on the key "Apple"
The hash is converted into a bucket index
The key-value pair is stored in that bucket
Buckets (Core Idea)

HashMap stores data in an array of buckets:

[0] → null  
[1] → (Apple, 10)  
[2] → (Banana, 20) → (Mango, 30)

👉 Each bucket can contain:

one element
or multiple elements (in case of collisions)
Collision (Very Important)

A collision happens when two keys go to the same bucket.

hash("A") → 2  
hash("B") → 2

👉 Both keys are stored in the same bucket

How Collisions Are Handled
Before Java 8:
stored as a LinkedList
Since Java 8:
if too many elements → converted into a Red-Black Tree

👉 This improves performance

get() Operation (Important)
map.get("Apple");

👉 What happens:

hashCode() of the key
find the bucket
iterate through elements in the bucket
use equals() to find exact match
Why equals() + hashCode() Together
hashCode() → finds the correct bucket
equals() → finds the exact key

👉 Both are required for correct behavior

Important Internal Details
Initial Capacity

Default:

16
Load Factor
0.75

👉 When:

size > capacity × loadFactor

→ resize happens

Resize (Rehashing)
a new array is created (usually doubled in size)
all elements are rehashed and redistributed

👉 This operation is expensive: O(n)

Time Complexity
Operation	Average	Worst
put()	O(1)	O(n)
get()	O(1)	O(n)
remove()	O(1)	O(n)

👉 Worst case is rare (thanks to tree structure in Java 8+)

Important Notes
no guaranteed order
allows one null key
not thread-safe
very fast due to hashing
Common Mistakes

❌ Not overriding equals() and hashCode()
❌ Using mutable objects as keys
❌ Expecting elements to be ordered

Example of a Bad Key
class User {
    String name;
}

👉 Without overriding equals() and hashCode(), this can break HashMap

When to Use HashMap
fast lookups
key-value data
order is not important
When NOT to Use
need order → use LinkedHashMap
need sorting → use TreeMap
multi-threading → use ConcurrentHashMap
Summary
HashMap uses hashing + buckets
works with hashCode() and equals()
very fast: O(1)
handles collisions with list/tree
resizes when capacity is exceeded
